<p>Once you add a page border or border you can decide whether or not
the border surrounds the header and footer. The page border may or may not
print completely, depending on the settings for the header and footer.</p>

<p>For example, if the footer is set to be "0"ù from the edge of the page
(which means right at the edge of the paper) and the page border is set to
surround the footer, the bottom of the page border will not print.</p>

<p>Let's learn how you can use the page border application and fix the
problem when the bottom of the border does not print.</p>


<div class="row">
<div class="twelve columns">
<h4>Printing Problems with Page Borders</h4>

<p>If part of the page border does not print correctly, click on Options in the
Borders and Shading Menu box. The Options button is above the OK button.</p>

<p>After selecting Options, the <strong>Border and Shading Options</strong> Box will open and you can change where the border art is placed on the page using this box.</p>

 <img class="img-wrap style1" src=
            "images/wordprocessing/bordershadingoptions.jpg">



<p>To do this, click on the drop down menu under the Measure from: section on
the menu. Change the option from "Edge of Page" to "Text"ù. Doing this
allows you to uncheck the "Surround header"ù and "Surround footer" boxes 
so that all of the border art can be printed on the page of your document.</p>

<p>Note, the page border will not print on the bottom of the page if the footer
is set too close to the edge of the bottom of the page and the border is set to
surround the footer.</p>

<p>Refer to Headers and Footers to recall how to change the space between the
header and footer and the edge of the page. You may want to adjust that setting
and leave the "surround header" and "surround footer"ù boxes checked 
when you try to fix the printing problem.</p>

